<DOC><DOCNO> AP890225-0040 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0709EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Protests     02-25 0312</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea-Protests,0325</SECOND><HEAD>Koreans Stage Anti-Bush, Anti-Government Protests</HEAD><BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Demonstrators today shouted anti-U.Sand anti-government slogans and threw firebombs at police duringprotests in several South Korean cities.   Riot police broke up the rallies, often forming a wall with theirshields. In some cities, police used tear gas and engaged in runningclashes with protesters.   Police officials said 25,000 riot police were on top alert inmetropolitan Seoul to block protests against the visit Monday ofPresident Bush. Bush and his wife, Barbara, arrived today in Beijingfor a weekend visit following a stopover in Tokyo for EmperorHirohito's funeral.   The turnout for today's protests was small, with no more than afew thousand people taking part nationwide. The protesters shoutedslogans, including ``Bush Go Home!'' and ``Down With Roh Tae-woo!''   The nation's largest dissident alliance issued a statementdemanding Bush cancel his visit, which it said was designed tobolster the government of South Korean President Roh Tae-woo. Rohmarks his first anniversary in office today.   ``The United States is scheming, through Bush's visit, toperpetuate the division of the Korean peninsula, stabilize themilitary dictatorship and heighten tensions,'' said the UnitedNational Democratic Movement of Korea.   About 500 radical students gathered at South Gate, one of Seoul'sancient city gates, and shouted slogans, but police dispersed themand arrested some. Police used tear gas to break up 200 studentsholding a rally near the Seoul railway station.   About 100 dissidents held a rally inside a downtown Seoul churchto demand Roh's ouster.   In the provincial city of Kwangju, riot police blocked a plannedrally, and students and farmers armed with rocks and firebombsfought running battles with police, who fired tear gas, the newsagency Yonhap said.   Dissidents also have called for protest rallies Monday to opposethe Bush visit.</TEXT></DOC>